The Department of State Services (DSS) wishes to inform the public that it did not arrest Ibrahim MAGU, Acting Chairman of the Economic and Financial Crimes Commission (EFCC) as has been reported by sections of the media. The Service, has since, today, 6th July, 2020, been inundated with enquiries over the alleged arrest. Peter Afunanya, Ph.DPublic Relations Officer,Department of State Services,National Headquarters,Abuja6th July, 2020 PRNigeria The Department of State Services (DSS) has arrested Ibrahim Magu, acting chairman of the Economic and Financial Crimes Commission (EFCC). TheCable understands that DSS operatives arrived the EFCC headquarters in Abuja Monday afternoon and quietly whisked him away without creating any scene. His arrest comes a few days after Abubakar… July 6, 2020 In "News" By Chibuike Nwabuko Abuja (Sundiata Post) -  Acting President, Prof Yemi Osinbajo's bold initiative to settle the rift between the Economic and Financial Crimes Commission (EFCC), and the Department of State Services (DSS), has started yielding result as the two agencies  are collaborating to investigate, recover, arrest and possibly prosecute top security… August 12, 2018 In "Top Stories" By Moji Eniola Ikeja - An Ikeja High Court will on April 18 rule on the admissibility of a report by the Department of State Services (DSS) to the Senate on Mr Ibrahim Magu, the Acting Chairman of the Economic and Financial Crimes Commission (EFCC). The News Agency of Nigeria… February 28, 2019 In "News"